WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.283
Say your music app plays you a song you love, by a band you have never heard of.

2
00:00:06.283 --> 00:00:13.036
Two descriptions get compared in a data center and the verdict comes back: same taste.

3
00:00:13.036 --> 00:00:16.256
But weigh what that comparison has to do.

4
00:00:16.256 --> 00:00:18.219
A song is not one number.

5
00:00:18.219 --> 00:00:25.287
It is loud, fast, sad, bright, many qualities at once, and your taste is that same tangle.

6
00:00:25.287 --> 00:00:32.198
No single ruler works here, because the ruler that measures loud says nothing about sad.

7
00:00:32.198 --> 00:00:39.659
And waiting for two tangles to agree on every quality at once is a lottery you would never win,

8
00:00:39.659 --> 00:00:45.941
so the comparison needs a principled way to collapse many measurements into one.

9
00:00:45.941 --> 00:00:47.198
So try it first.

10
00:00:47.198 --> 00:00:53.952
How would you boil the match between two many-featured things down to a single number?

11
00:00:53.952 --> 00:00:55.679
Harder than it sounds.

12
00:00:55.679 --> 00:00:59.920
One answer to it runs half of modern machine learning.

13
00:01:00.597 --> 00:01:05.934
You just tried to score that match by hand, and it fought back.

14
00:01:05.934 --> 00:01:10.254
Add everything up and loudness wins, not agreement.

15
00:01:10.254 --> 00:01:14.066
Count exact matches and nothing ever matches.

16
00:01:14.066 --> 00:01:16.692
Here is the move that lands it.

17
00:01:16.692 --> 00:01:21.013
A taste is an arrow: each direction is one quality,

18
00:01:21.013 --> 00:01:25.333
and the length is how hard the song leans that way.

19
00:01:25.333 --> 00:01:28.891
The recipe is almost embarrassingly small.

20
00:01:28.891 --> 00:01:33.042
Multiply the two arrows entry by entry, then add.

21
00:01:33.042 --> 00:01:37.955
If your taste is two and one, and a song is one and three,

22
00:01:37.955 --> 00:01:42.106
that is two times one plus one times three: five.

23
00:01:42.106 --> 00:01:45.410
One number, the whole tangle collapsed.

24
00:01:45.410 --> 00:01:47.443
Now meet the instrument.

25
00:01:47.443 --> 00:01:51.171
One probe arrow, the thing doing the asking.

26
00:01:51.171 --> 00:01:58.710
Four candidates, holding still, and under each candidate a bar showing its current score.

27
00:01:58.710 --> 00:02:01.929
Before anything moves, call your shot,

28
00:02:01.929 --> 00:02:09.553
and make it one the sweep can prove wrong: as the probe turns, does any score go negative?

29
00:02:09.553 --> 00:02:15.229
Now the sweep, and everything on screen is frozen except the probe.

30
00:02:15.229 --> 00:02:19.888
As the probe turns toward a candidate, that bar climbs.

31
00:02:19.888 --> 00:02:22.514
As it turns away, the bar dies.

32
00:02:22.514 --> 00:02:29.630
The candidates never moved, so direction is the only thing the score can be reading.

33
00:02:29.630 --> 00:02:33.951
So a big score means two songs are the same, right?

34
00:02:33.951 --> 00:02:36.238
Now watch what length does.

35
00:02:36.238 --> 00:02:42.676
One candidate stretches longer, direction pinned, and its bar climbs anyway,

36
00:02:42.676 --> 00:02:47.759
on length alone, even though its direction never got closer.

37
00:02:47.759 --> 00:02:52.248
The score reads agreement of direction, not sameness,

38
00:02:52.248 --> 00:02:55.637
and a long arrow can fake a high number.

39
00:02:55.637 --> 00:02:58.666
Look at what your hands just learned.

40
00:02:58.666 --> 00:03:03.004
Point the probe along a candidate and the sum climbs.

41
00:03:03.004 --> 00:03:06.360
Point it across and the sum dies to zero.

42
00:03:06.360 --> 00:03:09.880
Point it against and the sum goes negative.

43
00:03:09.880 --> 00:03:14.873
One multiply and add, and it behaves like a meter with agree,

44
00:03:14.873 --> 00:03:17.411
ignore, and oppose on the dial.

45
00:03:17.411 --> 00:03:22.077
So say it plainly: the dot product is a similarity meter.

46
00:03:22.077 --> 00:03:24.287
Two lists of numbers go in.

47
00:03:24.287 --> 00:03:27.725
One honest reading of alignment comes out.

48
00:03:27.725 --> 00:03:34.437
And the reading tracks direction, because direction is all the sweep ever changed.

49
00:03:34.437 --> 00:03:36.338
Time to close the loop.

50
00:03:36.338 --> 00:03:40.306
Rebuild the meter from memory: two arrows go in,

51
00:03:40.306 --> 00:03:44.852
and which two operations turn them into a single score?

52
00:03:44.852 --> 00:03:49.151
Hold your answer while the opening scene comes back.

53
00:03:49.151 --> 00:03:54.358
Your app played you a stranger's song and called it your taste.

54
00:03:54.358 --> 00:03:56.673
You know what that took now.

55
00:03:56.673 --> 00:03:58.657
Your taste is the probe.

56
00:03:58.657 --> 00:04:03.865
The catalog is a shelf of candidates, thousands of arrows long.

57
00:04:03.865 --> 00:04:09.072
And the machine in the data center is the thing you just built,

58
00:04:09.072 --> 00:04:15.107
running multiply-and-add a few million times and handing you the top bar.

59
00:04:15.107 --> 00:04:19.157
That was the whole mystery: your meter, at scale.

60
00:04:19.157 --> 00:04:22.925
Now the honest look, and guess before you watch.

61
00:04:22.925 --> 00:04:25.358
You saw length raise the score.

62
00:04:25.358 --> 00:04:26.614
But by how much?

63
00:04:26.614 --> 00:04:29.989
Double c1's length exactly, same direction,

64
00:04:29.989 --> 00:04:35.327
just twice as long: does the score double exactly, or just drift up?

65
00:04:35.327 --> 00:04:36.897
It doubles, exactly.

66
00:04:36.897 --> 00:04:41.528
Four point two becomes eight point four, to the last digit.

67
00:04:41.528 --> 00:04:48.043
Double one input, double the output: the meter is linear in each arrow you feed it.

68
00:04:48.043 --> 00:04:50.554
That clean scaling is the crack.

69
00:04:50.554 --> 00:04:56.755
A loud song wins on sheer loudness, whether or not the taste underneath agrees,

70
00:04:56.755 --> 00:05:00.837
because size passes straight through the arithmetic.

71
00:05:01.490 --> 00:05:02.992
Take it with you.

72
00:05:02.992 --> 00:05:06.438
A song and a taste, folded into arrows,

73
00:05:06.438 --> 00:05:12.889
collapsed by multiply-and-add into one score: a meter with a crack in it.

74
00:05:12.889 --> 00:05:19.604
One more aisle, to make sure it lands: score yourself against a job posting.

75
00:05:19.604 --> 00:05:23.669
Same multiply-and-add, one number for the fit.

76
00:05:23.669 --> 00:05:25.878
Now invent your own pair.

77
00:05:25.878 --> 00:05:31.974
Anything you can describe as two matching lists, the meter can score.

78
00:05:31.974 --> 00:05:39.927
For the walk home: what is the cheapest fix that keeps the direction and forgets the size?

79
00:05:39.927 --> 00:05:40.722
Still up?

80
00:05:40.722 --> 00:05:44.610
The menu below has three ways to keep going.
